{"key":"processedPost-17445403","value":{"id":17445403,"first":17444806,"last":17446513,"when":1356446132,"utime":"12/25/12 04:35 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>Guitar Freak said:</b><br />i got that,&nbsp; i know that mushrooms receive a large percentage out of the air but also from the cake itself, if water were to condense on to the cake would this not hydrate it?<br /></blockquote><br /><br />I'd suggest to follow established technique on your first few grows.&nbsp; The mushrooms receive moisture from the substrate.&nbsp; Humidity helps to keep the substrate from drying out as fast.&nbsp; Falling moisture(rain) from a humidifier will saturate the substrate and prevent fruiting.&nbsp; You're supposed to have a fluctuating humidity to stimulate evaporation which is the main pinning trigger, and then you carefully replace that moisture by misting.<br /><br />Trying to maintain a steady-state moisture content in substrates or the air will result in poor fruiting performance.<br />RR","title":"Re: Mycology Tec","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}